    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Play About the War</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Mark E Abels letter criticizes Wilton, Conn, board of education for canceling high school play about Iraq war</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Canceled by Principal, Student Play Is Headed to Off Broadway'' (news article, April 12):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Canceled by Principal, Student Play Is Headed to Off Broadway'' (news article, April 12):</p>
        <p>Every once in a while you read something that is just stunning in its arrogance. You report that the Wilton, Conn., school board has ''cleared the way'' for a group of young people (presumably American citizens possessed of basic civil rights), acting with their own resources and on their own time, to present their own work at a private venue in another state.</p>
        <p>The school board magnanimously will not try to stop them. How sporting of the members of the Wilton board of education! Hats off to them.</p>
        <p>Mark E. Abels  St. Louis, April 12, 2007</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
